note.p: This very compact, early sixteenth-century manuscript seems to have been a vade mecum used by the Islay Beatons but possibly partly inscribed in Ireland. Its main components are a Latin text of Psalm 118 (now Psalm 119) by Niall Mac Beathadh and a collection of "medical definitions" by the Irish scribe, Maol Sheachlainn mac Iollainn Mhic an Leagha Ruaidh. The latter also contextualises medicine as a whole within cosmological and philosophical thought. Various maxims in a similar vein have been added elswhere in the manuscript in other, mostly Beaton-associated hands.

summary.p: Apart from a very short colophon, Niall Mac Beathadh's text of Psalm 118 (119) is entirely in Latin, so the only the medico-philosophical definitions are included in this transcription. These are often also in Latin but with Gaelic translation and commentary. These consist of a pair of definitions on fol. 24r, an isolated couplet on fol. 25v, and the major collection of definitions beginning on fol. 26r.

support.p: Vellum; 6 × 4.5 cm (Black 2011); the manuscript is still in its original leather skin, which appears to have been designed for maximum protection and portability (McRoberts 1968: 171), suggesting it was of practical use.

condition.p: Mostly very good; there are a few short sections where the writing surface is badly damaged (fols 42r–43r, fol. 82v).

layoutDesc.p: Text is presented in continuous lines within a stout text block that occupies most of each page. Words are often split across manuscript lines. New definitions are often introduced with a capital and sometimes, when the referent also begins a new line, it is projected slightly into the margin. Otherwise the layout is uniform. Display script is briefly employed on fol. 37v.

origin.p: The hands of two known members of the Islay branch of the Beaton medical family appear in the manuscript: Níall and his son, Níall Óg. Another, unidentified hand (Hand24) elsewhere provides a first-person account of medical activity in Islay. It thus seems likely that the manuscript was at least partly written there. However, the collection of "medical definitions", which makes up the bulk of the manuscript, was written Maol Sheachlainn mac Iollainn Mhic an Leagha Ruaidh and there is no evidence that he ever left Ireland. Since there is also no evidence of scribal collaboration within the manuscript between him and any of the Beatons, the manuscript may well have begun its existence in Ireland.

Níall and Níall Óg were both active in the first half of the sixteenth century (Bannerman 2015: 142; Mac an Leagha Ruaidh's contribution seems to have predated theirs. His statement that he is working for Níall Óg would suggests a similar period for his activity.

provenance.p: As noted above, large swathes of the manuscript may well have been written in Ireland, but extensive work on it evidently also took place in Islay.

acquisition.p: The manuscript was purchased in 1736 by the Advocates Library from Robert Freebairn. It may also have been owned by Rev. John Beaton (Black 2011).

note.p: A number of works associated with Avicenna could be undestood by the abbreviation ".c̄.". The provisional identification here is of the Al-Qanun fi't-Tibb, or "Canon of Medicine". This will be resolved, of course, by locating the quotation in an identified text.
